I love my body

4 words I never thought i’d ever be able to say and truly mean it. 

From as young as i can remember i always hated my body. i wasn’t slim enough, i didn’t have curves, i didn’t have visible abs, i didn’t have perky boobs, i didn’t have a plump bum, the list goes on. I would find everything wrong with my body. 

I spent 9 years of my life criticizing how I looked and sacrificed my health in attempts to fit a certain body standard - only to still be unhappy with how I looked. 

One day I decided enough was enough and I was gonna go on a journey of self-love and ever since I haven’t looked back. I devoted time and effort into learning how to love myself internally, which then reflected how I felt about myself externally. 

Here are some things I began doing:
☁️ Meditation and deep breathing
☁️ Taking time to myself and doing things I enjoy (ex. getting my nails done, reading romance novels, just overall things that made me happy!) 
☁️ Journaling my thoughts, how I was feeling, my goals in life and finding my purpose 
☁️ Doing things because I enjoyed them, not because I had to
☁️ Read lots and lots of self-love & self-help books 
☁️ Challenged myself in certain aspects of life because growth doesn’t occur in your comfort zone (ex. began opening up more about my ED, began taking creatine which resulted in weight gain)
☁️ Looked for the little good things in every situation 
☁️ Accepted my past and began putting my focus toward the future

If you are in a place where you are in the continuous cycle of self-hate, you can end it. Putting time into bettering yourself is the best investment you’ll ever make.

🤍the time of the month 
🤍how much you’ve been lifting : pbs, strength, form, energy levels 
🤍muscle vs fat gain
🤍water retention / hydration levels 
🤍physical changes, your body image 

i can literally go on forever, but you get the point. don’t allow the scale make you feel any less worthy because it’s just a number🤍

the main turning point to truly loving my body was when i realized that i needed to appreciate and get comfortable with my natural, unposed body 

i slowly became accepting of how i looked naturally, and that’s when my confidence began to increase

you see, posing and looking “your best” is cute and all, but it’s so important to understand that you don’t always look like that. and that’s fine! no one is posed 24/7!

it’s important to remember not to compare yourself to those you see online, because they are human too and have a body that functions the exact same way yours does 

our bodies naturally fold when we sit or move a certain way

we get bloated and our tummy expands after we eat

we have cellulite, stretch marks, and scars 

in real life, you’re usually not posing. you’re going on with your normal daily routine, so get comfortable and appreciate how you look naturally. 

your unposed body is just as cute and as worthy as your posed body 🫶🏻

the past few weeks i’ve had terrible body image days…

but the thing is i no longer allow bad body image days to dictate my whole day. i don’t revert to unhealthy habits like how i used to

even if i’m bloated or don’t like how i look, i’ll still wear cute fits, including tight clothes bc life is too short to allow a bad body image day to stop you from being your best self

this is your reminder if you’re having a bad body image day 

🤍 you still need to eat just as much as you regularly would
🤍 wear clothes that make you comfortable, if you wanna wear baggy clothes bc it helps you not focus on how your body looks - do it
🤍 distract yourself, do things you love, get your mind off of how your body looks
🤍 and most importantly - recognize that this bad body image day will PASS 

put on a cute fit for the day and we move 🫡

and that’s completely fine. but on those days, remember that your worth is not determined by how you look or how you perceive yourself

when you find yourself talking negatively about your body, appearance, or yourself as a whole. take a step back. 

it is so important to stop yourself for a second and to RECOGNIZE the negative thoughts you are thinking

because from there, you can go okay, this is a negative thought, i have many thoughts throughout the day, but i will not allow this one thing to dictate my whole day. 

look in the mirror, tell yourself you’re a bada$$, put on a cute fit, and go on with your day. don’t allow one, or a few negative thoughts ruin your whole day.

TW: ED & TRAUMA 

I thought I would share this story as it is has been a major realization in my life recently and to share some interesting information you may not know (or have even experienced yourself). 

At a point in our lives, we have / will face a traumatic event. At the age of 15, one of my brothers passed away. For years I had pushed away the negative feelings associated with my grief, and well here I am 7 years later with it coming to bite me in the a$$.

I used to think that after a certain amount of months, grief/trauma is something that should fade, but it doesn’t. A month ago, I took a scary step which was learning about grief/trauma by picking up a book called ‘What’s your grief?’.

This was a late, but massive step in my healing journey. While reading this book, I learned that there is a direct correlation of experiencing trauma and developing an eating disorder.

A couple months after my brothers passing, I had fallen into the habit of restricted eating behaviours. I never knew the root of the problem, I always just assumed it was because of social media. After reading the book, I realized that there was a lot more to it than that…

THE LINK BETWEEN EDS + TRAUMA

Multiple studies have shown that people who have experienced trauma are more susceptible to eating disorders. Studies have also shown, the earlier trauma occurs in someones life, the more intense of an outcome.

Eating disorders are never entirely about food. They are a mental disorder, a way to ‘control’ a specific aspect in ones life.

After experiencing trauma, an individual feels a sense of powerlessness and that they have no control over the event. Restriction and binging behavoiurs is a (negative) coping mechanism that serves to give an individual a sense of control. Controling what you’re eating is also a means of self-protection, allowing an individual to escape the emotions associated with trauma.

I’m now 3 years recovered from my ED and just now found the link to why it may have really began in the first place.

something i’m sure we’re all guilty of doing at least one time in our lives…

not eating or eating a small amount before a day out where we knew we would be in a bikini or tight clothes that show off our body 

guilty of it myself, I genuinely cannot even put a number to the amount of times I used to do it in highschool

the days I wouldn’t eat so i wouldn’t be bloated and looked as thin as possible, sacrificing not only my physical health but mental health

this is your reminder:

whether you’re going to be in a bikini all day or tight clothes - YOU NEED TO EAT. food is what will fuel you and your body for the day & with maximize your energy and overall happiness. you cannot live a full life on an empty stomach. 

take it from someone who’s skipped eating before a day out  many times , ITS NOT WORTH IT. you deserve to eat. don’t allow your mind to bully your body 🫶🏻

GYM TIPS + ADVICE FOR BEGINNERS 

 FIND YOUR BALANCE ⚖️

one thing i struggled with at the beginning of my fitness journey was finding balance. i became obsessed with the gym and had little to no social life. i would skip out on being with my friends to go to the gym or to “avoid” eating unhealthy. just because you’re going to the gym & beginning a healthy lifestyle doesn’t mean you can’t enjoy yourself! it’s important to take time to be social & have fun. find what works for you and go with it - balance looks different for everyone so don’t compare what your fitness / social life looks like to someone else’s. 

DONT RELY ON THE SCALE 📈

a common mistake people make is relying on the scale to track progress. an increase / decrease in the number on the scale will vary from day to day, for a number of reasons ( water intake , the time of the month, sleep, stress etc etc). there are so many other ways to track progress , for example :

~ taking progress pics
~ how your clothes fit
~ gaining strength in exercises 
~ your mood! your body is not the only thing that’s  changing during the beginning of your fitness journey. it’s important to reflect on other aspects of your life that are improving that don’t relate to how you look

PLAN YOUR WORKOUTS 🏋🏼‍♀️

to avoid being anxious before/ when getting to the gym it’s important you go in knowing what you’re doing. personally, i have a fitness app that i use that has multiple different workout guides that allow me to track my progress. there are so many helpful fitness apps and i really recommend investing in one. if you don’t want to do that, another option is writing down your own workouts in your notes to follow, get inspo from instagram, google, youtube , etc.

DON’T START A DIET YOU DONT SEE YOURSELF MAINTAINING LONG-TERM 🥗

the biggest mistake i made starting my fitness journey was the “all or nothing” mindset i had when it came to healthy eating. restricting myself from food enjoyed lead me to develop an eating disorder. something i go by is : “if you don’t see yourself eating like this for the rest of your life - don’t do it”. you can eat ‘good food’ +  enjoy sweets and still be healthy. 

#gymtips #gymadvice

WHY YOU SHOULD BE DOING CARDIO + STRENGTH TRAINING 🏃🏼‍♀️

adding a combination of cardio & strength training into my workout routine has been a game changer. 

by doing both cardio & strength training, i’ve seen a drastic difference in my mental health & physical abilities

the past 4 months, i’ve added cardio into my workout routine. this includes walking, hiking, running & circuit training.

cardio is known to improve muscle endurance. since cardio pumps blood & oxygen more efficiently through your body the muscles you train have a better ability to recover and build. 

i’ve noticed that i’ve been able to do more reps with ease compared to before i started doing cardio (ex yesterday i was able to squat 205lbs for 4 reps, whereas for MONTHS i was stuck at 2 reps)

anywayssss, don’t skip doing cardio because it is great for many reasons - aka improves muscle endurance & nothing feels better than repping out a weight you never thought you would be able to 🤪

idk who needs to hear this but… taking time away from the gym is not going to ruin all the progress you’ve made

when i first started going to the gym & had to take time away i thought it was the end of the world & that all my muscles would deflate LOL

this is NOT the case!!! taking time away from the gym is extremely beneficial for SO many reasons, to name a few:

☁️ allows for your body to re-build broken down muscle tissue
☁️ re-motivates (as someone who has been going to the gym for years, after a while i just get bored and the gym becomes a chore.  sometimes taking some time away is all you need to get that extra boost of motivation to smash your workouts ✨)
☁️ opens up time for you to focus on other aspects of life (spending time with friends & family, finding new hobbies & spending time becoming comfortable of your own company)
☁️ prevents muscle fatigue!!

i remember taking the first video like it was just yesterday 

it was my first week of uni. being away from scheduled home cooked meals to having to make my own food or buy food from the cafes on campus. me being scared of food, i lived off of banana bread and fruit for the first year of uni. 

of course i HAD to do a body check to ensure that i hadn’t gained weight after the first week. 

then to the second video - in my second year of uni when covid hit , i was back at home. at that time my ED was out of hand and i knew i needed professional help. i began learning how to listen to my hunger cues & saw an ED specialist for 6 months. 

while learning to listen to my hunger cues - i gained 20lbs. it was hard seeing my body change but i knew i had to keep pushing myself. i couldn’t relapse, i couldn’t go back to the state i was in. 

fast forward to the last video - my body has found the weight it’s meant to be at. 2 years fully recovered now. i workout because it makes me feel good not to look a certain way. i’m no longer scared of eating out or eating too much - i enjoy myself without any intrusive thoughts. 

i’m the happiest i’ve ever been, confident in myself and my abilities & in a stable healthy relationship. 

if you’re struggling - please know there is light and happiness at the end of the tunnel 💓

UNDERSTANDING YOUR CYCLE 🔄

ever wonder why one week you feel your on the top of the world, and then the next week you feel like absolute sh*t? one week youre hitting PRs and the next you can barely move weight that you deem ‘light’ ?

i definitely did - and that’s why i started doing some research & realized that we go through what is called the menstrual cycle every month!

it’s extremely important to know what’s going on with your body & what’s impacting your day-to-day tasks, so i created a lil ‘THE 4 STAGE MENSTRUAL CYCLE EXPLAINED’ 

Phase 1 - Menstrual Phase 

The menstrual phase is the first day of your period.  During your menstrual phase, you energy is at its lowest, you may be feeling withdrawn, have a low mood and feel discomfort.

During this time it is important to take a day or two to yourself and relax. 

Phase 2 - Follicular Phase 

This phase begins the day after your period ends. During this phase, your estrogen and testosterone begin to rise, giving you more energy and often improves your mood. 

The estrogen being released makes you feel more extroverted and energetic! During this time it’s good to start pushing yourself in the gym again and go out with your friends.

Phase 3 - Ovulatory Phase 

Estrogen and testosterone rise to their peak during this time, which results in boosting the effects you felt during the follicular phase. During this phase, keep pushing yourself in the gym as this time is when you will be feeling your strongest and most energetic. 

This is the time to hit PRs and do intense workouts as your body has the ability to do so. The ovulatory phase is when you will be feeling your most confident as well as feeling your best in all areas of life (physical , sexual , emotional etc).

PHASE 4 CONTINUED IN COMMENTS ⬇️

first off- what is creatine?

creatine is a substance that is made by the human body in the liver, kidneys, and pancreas. It is then converted into phosphocreatine and stored in the muscles, where it is used for energy.  The main reason people take supplemented creatine is to improve athletic performance and gain muscle mass. 

THE BENEFITS:

✨helps muscle cells produce more energy
✨ add muscle mass
✨ improves high intensity performance
✨speeds up muscle growth
✨reduces resistance to fatigue
✨it’s easy to use!!

10 things i’ve learned on my fitness journey ⬇️

1. proper form is more important than the amount of weight you lift. tell your ego to sit down - don’t sacrifice your form just to lift a heavier weight. bad form can = to injuries and time out of the gym 

2. rests days are just as important as training days. cherish your rest days and make sure to take at least 1 every week. your body needs it. 

3. working out can be done in many different ways- going to the gym isn’t the only effective way to exercise

4. not everyday you’re going to feel 100% and motivated, but you learn to go anyway because exercise is a privilege 

5. don’t be afraid to learn and try new exercises. you are working out to better yourself, don’t judge yourself if you can’t do something on the first try. you get good at something by practicing and being consistent. 

6. there will be weeks when you are unable to lift as heavy as usual - it is totally normal 

7. nobody is looking at you or judging you at the gym - we’re all too busy working and focusing on ourselves 

8. the gym will always be there - it’s not the end of the world if you miss a session. don’t beat yourself up over it, in a month time you won’t even remember you missed a session

9. missing a session here and there will not ruin your progress. if you are overall consistent, results will show. 

10. you need to be patient. fitness is a life long journey, appreciate it. there will be times where you’re able to smash your workouts every week, and other times when you skip the gym and life gets it the way

#gymgirl #gymtips #fitnessmotivation #fitnessjourney

restricting your food intake does not = sustainable weight loss. finding balance does. 

for years of my life, i associated weight loss only being attainable through food restriction & excessive amounts of exercise. 

yeah, doing this worked in the short-term & i lost weight, but keeping my weight down was an struggle. since i lost weight in a way i couldn’t sustain long-term, i ended up binging & developing an ED. i gained all the weight back, felt like sh*t in myself, and started restricting again. it was a never ending cycle. 

if you are currently in a state where you’re trying to lose weight, TAKE. IT. SLOW. 

you don’t need to exercise twice a day. you don’t need to cut out your favourite foods and just eat chicken and rice for every meal. 

what you need to do is find what works for you. of course eating healthy is essential for your well-being and weight loss, but so is eating the foods you enjoy. find a sustainable diet that works for YOU - don’t feel like you need to follow what other people are saying they eat online for their “balance”. everyone’s balance looks different. 

overall, my rule of thumb is this: don’t start a diet you can’t see sustaining for the rest of your life. if you can’t enjoy your life while trying to lose weight, it’s likely not going to be sustainable long-term.
